CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39 year old right handed male with daily headaches, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine,  Zolpidem, Elavil, Cymbalta, Norvasc, Gabapentin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and primarily asleep EEG with photic stimulation but without hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and posts.   The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and has limited wakefulness.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The primarily sleep EEG could be due to sleep deprivation or other disturbances like hypersomnolence, or even a sleep-deprived EEG. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  37 year old woman with stroke, left-sided hemangioma.
MEDICATIONS: Oxycodone,  Elavil, Diovan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta, followed by delta and then vertex waves and POSTS. Hyperventilation does produce background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:	70 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with a feeling of disequilibrium
and presyncope, admitted in July 2009.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10
Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in background slowing. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes,
spindles and POSTS. The patient is quite sleepy and transitions in and out of stage II
sleep. The POSTS are of slightly higher amplitude on the left. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The
amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old female presented with syncope and toe ulceration.
MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the
record. There is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified. Features of drowsiness
including increase in beta followed by vertexes, K complexes, and spindles. With
arousal, the patient does achieve an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed in the
record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old woman with multiple events in the clinic today admitted with episode of unresponsiveness  and mutism.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  The patient is awake and cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well defined 9.3 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage fronto-central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of rhythmic theta.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this record was
recorded immediately after this patient's multiple and prolonged events. Hence, not only were the behaviors unusual for seizures, but there was no postictal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old right handed woman with seizure versus
nonepileptic seizures characterized by an aura of lightheadedness, generalized shaking
with loss of consciousness. History of pseudotumor cerebri.
Topamax, Diamox, Klonopin, Prozac, Seroquel, Ambien.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there was a 10 Hz alpha rhythm
with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral
driving.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. If epilepsy is a
strong consideration, a repeat tracing captured in sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	67 year old woman with bipolar disease,  episode of loss of consciousness with confusion following the use of Wellbutrin. Syncope vs seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Zyprexa, Simvastatin
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic simulation was completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG is appropriately organized with 10 Hz, 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of
low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed.  Normal electroencephalogram does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this is markedly improved compared to the previous study when she was admitted to the
hospital.  If epilepsy is an important consideration a follow-up study may be more intense, but in case this study is markedly improved.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	41   year old right handed male with recurrent panic attacks and syncopal episodes.
MEDICATIONS:  Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.   This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness including increasing beta.  Brief stage II sleep is observed followed by spontaneous arousals.  Hyperventilation produces an increasing amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep and does elicit scant driving.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed. The sleepiness and the generalized beta may be due to the patient's medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  	20 year old female with migraine headaches.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with posterior slow waves of youth.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing and a small degree of disorganization.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed.   Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  47 year old right handed male with alcohol-related seizures x 2 years.
MEDICATIONS:   None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation  are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements. Brief epochs of stage 1 sleep are seen with vertex waves followed by arousals. Hyperventilation produces and increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation does not elicit driving.
HR:   60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Patient's prior EEG in 2008 was also normal.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old female presented with shaking spells associated with hypoglycemia, diabetes, hypertension, and heavy menstruation.
MEDICATIONS: Humalog, Enalapril
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, there is a well defined 10Hz alpha rhythm. There is a little bit  of head rocking artifact.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase  in amplitude of the background. Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous rhythm slowing.  Brief epochs of stage I sleep are observed.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	80 year old woman with recent trauma status post fall due to unsteady gait. Had episode of eye twitching and myoclonic jerking of the arms and episodically of the legs. Indications to rule out seizure activity. Past medical history of A. fib, TIA, pacemaker.

MEDICATIONS:  Cymbalta, Percocet,  ASA,Cymbalta, Clonazepam, Vicodin, Lovenox, Lotensin, Norvasc, Loratadine

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  of EKG. Photic simulation was performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is a well-organized symmetric EEG. There is alpha of 8-9 Hz throughout the record. The amplitude is mildly high for patient's age but this is nonspecific. There is some muscle artifact due to shaking episodes, however there are no EEG correlates to the shaking activity. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

HR: 	72 bpm and  regular.


IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:   There is no epileptiform activity. There are no focal features. This study is improved compared to prior EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old male with recurrent episodes of syncope for the past 2 years. This occurs twice a week where he feels lightheaded, dizzy and hot and awakens on the floor having hit his head.
MEDICATIONS: Risperdal, Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 1 0.5 Hz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by occasional bursts of paroxysmal slowing following by vertex waves. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important concern, an outpatient ambulatory EEG may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old woman with migraine headache and dizziness.

MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Elmiron, Prilosec, Verapamil, Topamax, Sanctura,
Amitriptyline
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with a relatively high amplitude 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record and increases the amplitude of the background. In drowsiness, bursts of hypersynchronous slowing are observed. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old right handed woman with otitis this past Fall, history gamma knife surgery for brain tumor, ESRD and Hepatitis C.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 35-year-old woman with short-term memory loss, numbness in all extremities, and urinary urgency. Past history of childhood epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Birth control pills.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11-hZ alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. There is a small amount of low frontage frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta with occasional bursts of rhythmic frontal delta and rare vertex waves. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There were no epileptiform features identified. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If this patient continues to experience symptoms, which may be a seizure, additional EEG recording may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old right handed male with a tonic, clonic seizure 1
month ago, found to have a cavernous hemangioma pre-op for surgery on 02/10.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Oxcarbazepine, Amoxicillin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab .using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5hertz posterior
dominant rhythm. There is a small amount of theta observed in the temporal regions,
bilaterally. Features of drowsiness include an increase in synchronicity of the
background followed by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm, POSTS and then vertex
waves and spindles in stage II sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is
drifting off to sleep and does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 66bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL No epileptiform features were observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. There is a scant amount of background theta in the temporal regions in relaxed wakefulness particularly in the beginning of the record and a bit more so on the left, but not really outside of the-range of normal particularly with use of this patient's medications. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman with limited history, resident of the South. She reports having epilepsy and multiple falls with multiple medical problems. Long history of epilepsy but recently improved and her falling stopped.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Lipitor, Norvasc, Detrol, others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic simulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominate rhythm. A fair amount of muscle artifact, and a very modest beta. The patient appears to be nervous as indicated by frequent eye flutter. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response. Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits, but is remarkable for;
1. Generous beta.
2. Eye flutter.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above can be seen in the context of anxiety. The beta may be seen with the use of benzodiazepine. No epileptiform features were identified today. A follow up study may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old right handed woman with a syncopal event recently and a past history of childhood seizures.

MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background is somewhat low amplitude but there is an 11 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. There is generous artifact observed in the frontalis region with the frontal electrodes. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha and an increase in beta.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. No features of this individual's childhood epilepsy were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed female with a history of bipolar disease
and head trauma in 2009, who presented with memory loss and headache.
MEDICATIONS: Lisinopril, Risperidone, Nabumetone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized.
There is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm. There are some features of drowsiness
which hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing and vertex waves. Photic stimulation
produces scant driving. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal neuroepileptiform features are observed. The
hypersynchronous slowing is a normal finding in drowsiness.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old male with a history of herpes encephalitis in October
2009.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are completed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm. It,
at times, is slightly higher amplitude on the left compared to the right. The frequency is
identical, but the amplitude is approximately 25% higher on the left. Features of
drowsiness include attenuation of the background. Hyperventilation produces an
increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral
driving.

HR: 56 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG demonstrates a dramatic improvement in
comparison to the 2009 study demonstrating epileptiform activity in the right temporal
region, marked background slowing, and right temporal delta.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old woman with bipolar disease and an overdose or
Dilantin, Depakote and/or trazodone, seizure-free for some months.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Serax, Thiamine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system or electrode placement with 1 channel or EKG. There is no hyperventilation and
photic simulation performed for this record.
rhythm. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread or the alpha rhythm. This is
followed by an increase in beta. The patient looks to be falling asleep or has a posture
of someone who is sleeping actually when the EEG pattern demonstrates an awake

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG demonstrates a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  This is followed by an increase in beta.  The patient looks to be falling asleep or has a posture of someone who is sleeping  actually when the EEG pattern demonstrates an awake pattern.  This can be seen in normals or in someone who is actually somewhat sleepy.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

further information is needed, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages or sleep is

CLINICAL HISTORY: 24 year old male who had a 10-minute loss of consciousness and fell and hit his ear.

MEDICATIONS: Ambien, Nitroglycerine, Zofran, Lovenox, Albuterol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. Hyperventilation is performed while the patient is lying on his back and does not activate the record.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are noted. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old female 20 weeks pregnant with diabetes, history of coma during this pregnancy with blunt trauma to the head followed by 4 seizures on March 31 with tongue biting but no loss of consciousness or incontinence.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, (Lamictal)?

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The technologist is assisted by an aid, but the patient is not cooperative.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a small amount of low voltage central beta activity near 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm. The patient does not cooperate, particularly with testing, but in the awake record there is no epileptiform activity.

HR: 110 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is one of many EEGs for this young adult during this pregnancy. Over time, the focal features and the epileptiform features have resolved. The patient's poor cooperation would prohibit additional testing and additional testing to be deferred until such time that the patient can cooperate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old right handed female with refractory epilepsy, status post temporal lobectomy, recurrent seizures and migraine headaches. Current seizures are characterized by crying spells.

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal, Lyrica,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, fed through central beta activity. Nearly continuous focal slowing is observed from the left temporal region that is characterized by the presence of theta frequency activity as well as some description of faster frequency activity. Features of sleep include an increase in background slowing. Vertex waves are observed in stage I sleep. Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record nor does photic stimulation.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed today. The focal slowing Is an anticipated finding following craniotomy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 22 year old male with seizures, underlying hemiatrophy.

MEDICATIONS: Allegra

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz 40 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm with small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.
Hyperventilation produces some head rocking artifact and some rhythmic sign but no
definite focal features. In stage I sleep, vertex waves were identified. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive epileptiform features were observed,
although there was some head rocking artifact. If epilepsy is an important consideration
repeat tracing and capturing sleep is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 79 year old left handed male with new onset seizures, dementia.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Aricept, Namenda

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm
with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There is a small amount
of temporal theta noted in wakefulness and in the transition to drowsiness.
Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.

HR: 50 bpm and irregular

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no significant focal features observed. The
background is within normal limits for age. No epileptiform features were identified. If
epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old right handed female with epilepsy since 2007 with abnormal lesions found on MRI. Last seizure 2 weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-defined, 11.7 Hz, 50 microvolt alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in the amplitude of the background and an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a follow-up study may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 41 year old male with recurrent syncope with left-sided numbness, alcohol abuse, hepatitis and anemia.

MEDICATIONS: Lovenox, Atropine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an extremely well-organized, 10Hz 50 microvolt alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage (central beta) activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta with attenuation of the alpha. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving.

HR: 60bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal, healthy, vigorous pattern for an adult of this age. No epileptiform features were noted. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 26 year old right handed woman with complex partial epilepsy, seizure-free since age 13.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Prenatal vitamins.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving responses at 1 Hz and faster frequencies. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. There is a prominent photic stimulation response but no definitive epileptiform features were identified

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old gentleman with posttraumatic epilepsy, recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a 10.7 Hz, 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Early and drowsy in the series the appearance of theta activity and POSTS. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep, but there is a scant driving response. Vertex waves are observed in stage I sleep.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or using special activation procedures is suggested. Hyperventilation was not performed in this record and if there is no contraindication should be performed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old woman with epilepsy, sarcoid, evaluate for seizures. The patient has been having mini strokes.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10-Hz posterior dominant rhythm. As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background theta. The drowsy pattern is at the limits of organization in an adult of this age. Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is noted in the transition to and from sleep. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. Following photic stimulation, the patient transitions into stage 1 sleep with vertex waves.
HR: 60 bpm and slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the third EEG for this patient. No epileptiform features are observed. The transition to drowsiness is associated with a slight degree of disorganization but not out of the range of normal.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old woman with colitis, abdominal pain and episode's of
shaking.
MEDICATIONS: Lovenox, Naprosyn, Dilaudid, Mesalamine, Prednisone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized
with symmetric reactive 10.7 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low
voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Alpha squeak is noted. The patient is somewhat
drowsy and starts to transition into sleep. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the
record and produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation
does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 23 now with 2-3 seizures per day characterized by staring, postictal confusion for 1-2 minutes, last episode was 2 days ago.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes an 11 hertz, 40 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm. There is a small amount of background theta. Drowsiness is characterized by Increase in background slowing. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, increasing theta in the temporal regions as well as eye blink artifact. On some occasions, the alpha rhythm is a little higher amplitude activity on the left than the right.  There is a bit of head rocking activity on the right compared to the left.  Hyperventilation is performed early in the record, producing an increase in theta.  Following this, as the patient becomes drowsy, the EEG is a bit more synchronous with higher amplitude and more anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although there is some head rocking artifact in the background, there are no definitive focal or epileptiform features.  Given the head rocking artifact, a followup study, capturing extended sleep may be helpful in
characterizing epileptiform activity.  Alternatively, comparison with previous studies may also be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  28 year old woman, pregnant with twins, presents with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra
REASON FOR  STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient's EEG was reviewed using continuous spike and seizure detection software, in addition to the patient's learned event as well as nurses' notes.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a mild excessive amount of beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and stage III sleep, as well as stage IV.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   None
SEIZURE/EVENT:  During the recording, the patient presses the alarm around 7:39 p.m. and describes that she feels like she is going to have an event.  There are no EEG changes at that time.  At 09:24:51, the patient presses the alarm and starts shaking her body, arching her back, and stretching her legs.  She lifts up the sheets at times and cannot be seen in the video.  She continues to do this for about 7 to 8 minutes until nurses come in and she is unresponsive to questions.  She remains having irregular jerking movements.  During this entire time, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The episode captured during this EEG had no EEG correlate, which is consistent with a nonepileptic psychogenic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old man with a history of TBI in 1998, admitted after having an episode of tonic-clonic seizure, brought to the emergency department where he had another seizure and confusion.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.    Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old, right-handed female with new onset seizures since May 2012, during sleep with tongue biting and postictal confusion.  Her last seizure was in September 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard International 10-20 System of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring, hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 10-11 Hz in frequency, 70-75 microvolts in amplitudes seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed and multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 to 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

LENGTH OF PROCEDURE:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 31-year-old woman who presents with a history of generalized tonic/clonic convulsions associated with tongue biting and post-ictal confusion.  The last such event was on 1/7/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Both hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consisted of a well-formed and modulated 10.5 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Hyperventilation was performed with fair effort and does not produce significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in occipital driving.  During sleep a burst of diffuse theta and delta activity, as well as symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, and POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are captured.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 22-minute electroencephalogram.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine electroencephalogram does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old woman with impaired cognitive thinking processes and progressive left-sided numbness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dyazide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The technologist noted that this patient seemed to have stable cognition throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage 10 Hz alpha rhythm in the background with generous low voltage beta.  The patient seemed to be a bit drowsy, transitioning into stage I sleep with an increase in beta and in vertex waves followed by arousal.  Hyperventilation did not significantly active the record.  In fact, the patient seemed to be falling asleep at the end of hyperventilation with beta spindles characteristic of stage II sleep.  Other features of sleep included vertex waves and more subtle POSTS.  Sustained stage II sleep was more abundant in those vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS were noted.
The patient remained drowsy throughout photic stimulation which nonetheless, elicited a driving response.  By the end of photic stimulation, she was drifting back into stage II sleep.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This patient appears to be extremely sleepy.  Clinical correlation for hypersomnolence may be appropriate, but a sleep-deprived EEG could also produce these findings.

INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Heart rate:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old woman with childhood epilepsy, break through seizures in 2004 & 2009, with recurrent a seizure in recent weeks requiring medication adjustment. Seizures in 2004 described as left-sided shaking with incontinence of bladder, lasting up to 30 minutes, 1-2 times per year.
MEDICATIONS:  Unclear.  No longer Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory record with some head rocking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, alpha squeak was noted on occasion.  Other features of the drowsy pattern included an increase in background theta.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult over a 9 year period.  The last EEG demonstrated epileptiform activity was in 2004, demonstrating left temporal focal slowing and sharp waves and a single right central temporal sharp wave.  That EEG was recorded in closer proximity to for a clinical event.
A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
